{"title_page": "Alwyne", "text_new": "'''Alwyne''' is an English given name. Notable people with this name include:\n\n* [[Alwyne Compton (disambiguation)]]\n** [[Lord Alwyne Compton (bishop)]]\n** [[Lord Alwyne Compton (politician)]]\n* [[Alwyne Wilks]]\n* [[Alwyne Statham]]\n* [[John Alwyne Kitching]]\n* [[Alwyne Jan \"AJ\" Perez]]\n* [[Gilbert Byng Alwyne Russell]]\n* [[Alwyne Michael Webster Whistler]]\n\n{{given name}}\n[[Category:English-language given names]]\n", "text_old": "'''Alwyne'''is an English given name. Notable people with this name include:\n\n* [[Alwyne Compton]]\n** [[Lord Alwyne Compton (bishop)]]\n** [[Lord Alwyne Compton (politician)]]\n* [[Alwyne Wilks]]\n* [[Alwyne Statham]]\n* [[John Alwyne Kitching]]\n* [[Alwyne Jan \"AJ\" Perez]]\n* [[Gilbert Byng Alwyne Russell]]\n* [[Alwyne Michael Webster Whistler]]\n\n{{given name}}\n[[Category:English-language given names]]\n", "name_user": "LittleWink", "label": "safe", "comment": "link perWP:HOWTODAB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alwyne"}
{"title_page": "Rick Tillis", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| image               = \n| imagesize           = \n| name                = Rick Tillis\n| state_house         = Tennessee\n| state               = Tennessee\n| district            = 92nd\n| term_start          = 2016\n| term_end            = \n| preceded            = [[Billy Spivey]]\n| succeeded           = \n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| birth_name          = Thomas Richard Tillis\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1963|9|22}}\n| birth_place         = [[Jacksonville, Florida]], U.S.\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| alma_mater          = \n| spouse              = Terry\n| children            = \n| residence           = [[Lewisburg, Tennessee]]\n| occupation          = Jeweler, politician\n| relations           = [[Thom Tillis]] (brother)\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Richard Tillis''' (born September 22, 1963) is an American politician, currently serving as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]], representing the 92nd district. He was initially elected in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Votesmart.org}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in [[Jacksonville, Florida]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sos-tn-gov-files.s3.amazonaws.com/Pages%2055%20-%20164%20from%202017-2018BlueBook.pdf|title=Tennessee Blue Book 2017-2018|website=Sos-tn-gov-files.s3.amazonaws.com|format=PDF}}</ref> he is the younger brother of [[Thom Tillis]], a United States Senator from [[North Carolina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/f516795aab504fad9fc42862052d8df4|title=A look at key primary legislative races in Tennessee|date=July 29, 2018|website=Apnews.com}}</ref> After high school, Tillis earned his [[GED]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.capitol.tn.gov/house/members/h92.html|title=Rick Tillis - Representatives - TN General Assembly|website=www.capitol.tn.gov|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter earning his [[GED]], Tillis took courses to become an [[emergency medical technician]] and volunteer firefighter. Tillis later became a self-employed jeweler, and owns Tillis Jewelry in [[Lewisburg, Tennessee]].\n\nIn September 2019, Tillis stepped down from a House leadership position after he revealed that he had participated in an anonymous [[Twitter]] account that was critical of then Speaker of the House Glen Casada, who had resigned as Speaker in August 2019 after revelations of drug use by his Chief of Staff, Cade Cothren, were made public.[[Tennessee House of Representatives|Tennessee House]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tillis, Rick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Republicans]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n\n{{Tennessee-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| image               = \n| imagesize           = \n| name                = Rick Tillis\n| state_house         = Tennessee\n| state               = Tennessee\n| district            = 92nd\n| term_start          = 2016\n| term_end            = \n| preceded            = [[Billy Spivey]]\n| succeeded           = \n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| birth_name          = Thomas Richard Tillis\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1963|9|22}}\n| birth_place         = [[Jacksonville, Florida]], U.S.\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| alma_mater          = \n| spouse              = Terry\n| children            = \n| residence           = [[Lewisburg, Tennessee]]\n| occupation          = Jeweler, politician\n| relations           = [[Thom Tillis]] (brother)\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Richard Tillis''' (born September 22, 1963) is an American politician, currently serving as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]], representing the 92nd district. He was initially elected in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Votesmart.org}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in [[Jacksonville, Florida]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sos-tn-gov-files.s3.amazonaws.com/Pages%2055%20-%20164%20from%202017-2018BlueBook.pdf|title=Tennessee Blue Book 2017-2018|website=Sos-tn-gov-files.s3.amazonaws.com|format=PDF}}</ref> he is the younger brother of [[Thom Tillis]], a United States Senator from [[North Carolina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/f516795aab504fad9fc42862052d8df4|title=A look at key primary legislative races in Tennessee|date=July 29, 2018|website=Apnews.com}}</ref> After high school, Tillis earned his [[GED]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.capitol.tn.gov/house/members/h92.html|title=Rick Tillis - Representatives - TN General Assembly|website=www.capitol.tn.gov|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter earning his [[GED]], Tillis took courses to become an [[emergency medical technician]] and volunteer firefighter. Tillis later became a self-employed jeweler, and owns Tillis Jewelry in [[Lewisburg, Tennessee]].\n\nIn September 2019, Tillis resigned from a House leadership position after it was revealed that he had operated an anonymous [[Twitter]] account that was critical of fellow Republicans in the [[Tennessee House of Representatives|Tennessee House]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2019/09/04/tennessee-legislature-rep-rick-tillis-resigns-house-whip-post/2210922001/|title=Rep. Rick Tillis, facing scrutiny for role in anonymous Twitter account, resigns House leadership post|last=Ebert|first=Joel|website=The Tennessean|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tillis, Rick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Republicans]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n\n{{Tennessee-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John Crest", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rick_Tillis"}
{"title_page": "Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation", "text_new": "The Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation is a [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profit organization]]\u00a0founded by Adam Lowe in 2009 and located in Madrid, Spain. It develops new techniques in digital recording and processing to document artworks and cultural heritage of many different types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-factory-of-fakes|title=The Factory of Fakes: How a workshop uses digital technology to craft perfect copies of imperilled art|last=Zalewski|first=Daniel|date=21 November 2016|website=The New Yorker|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4f14250-ca3f-11e9-af46-b09e8bfe60c0|title=How digital scanning can help save art works and buildings|last=Dickson|first=Andrew|date=30 August 2019|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/madrid/2020/02/29/5e57cfacfdddfff83a8b471f.html|title=Los copiadores legales del arte antiguo|last=G\u00f3mez|first=Virginia|date=29 February 2020|website=El Mundo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoy.es/sociedad/taller-prodigios-20191109002812-ntvo.html|title=El taller de los prodigios|last=Guerrero|first=Jos\u00e9 Antonio|date=10 November 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/apollo-awards-digital-innovation-year/|title=Digital Innovation of the Year: The Apollo Awards 2014|last=|first=|date=03 December 2014|website=Apollo Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> It is known for its facsimiles (high-resolution physical copies) of sites and objects such as the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|title=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|last=Glass|first=Nick|date=15 November 2017|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> two monumental [[lamassu]] sculptures from [[Nimrud]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/mosul-statues-unveiling-scli-intl/index.html|title=Mosul takes delivery of recreated icons|last=Guy|first=Jack|date=28 October 2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/art-smashed-by-jihadists-rises-up-after-global-effort-g0dbphfd5|title=Art smashed by jihadists rises up after global effort|last=Keeley|first=Guy|date=22 October 2019|website=The Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jordantimes.com/news/region/replicas-assyrian-statues-smashed-daesh-unveiled-iraqs-mosul|title=Replicas of Assyrian statues smashed by Daesh unveiled in Iraq\u2019s Mosul|last=AFP|first=|date=24 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Sebastiano del Piombo|Borgherini Chapel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/372727/how-michelangelo-and-sebastianos-roman-chapel-was-recreated-in-london/|title=How Michelangelo and Sebastiano\u2019s Roman Chapel Was Recreated in London|last=McEwan|first=Olivia|date=17 April 2017|website=Hyperallergic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> The\u00a0 Foundation also mounts exhibitions and trains local communities across the world in the use of digital recording technologies, and is active in contemporary debates about the functions and value of facsimiles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/49/exhibitions|title=Exhibitions|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/171/trainings-collaborations|title=Trainings and Collaborations|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/the-apollo-podcast-adam-lowe/|title=The Apollo podcast: Adam Lowe|last=|first=|date=4 May 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> It states that its aim is to \u201cbreak down the barriers between traditional and digital arts and demonstrate the importance of documenting, monitoring, studying, recreating and disseminating the world\u2019s cultural heritage.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/aboutus|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFactum Foundation works closely with [[Factum Arte]], and was established in order to take over Factum Arte\u2019s non-profit work relating to cultural heritage.\u00a0 \n\n== Cultural heritage projects ==\nNotable facsimiles made by Factum Foundation include: \n\n* The [[KV62|tomb of Tutankhamun]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-24478909|title=Which would you rather visit - a fake tomb or a real one?|last=Gee|first=Alison|date=08 November 2013|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Rooms from the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]] in the [[Valley of the Kings]]. Scanning of all extant fragments from the tomb is underway, and Factum states that the finished facsimile of the tomb will be \u2018by some measures... even more complete than the original as it now stands\u2019, as it will incorporate fragments removed from the tomb in the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1502/the-tomb-of-seti-recording-and-facsimile|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> \u00a0\n* Two monumental lamassu and all extant wall and floor reliefs from the throne room of the North-West Palace of [[Ashurnasirpal II]] at Nimrud \n\n* The [[:it:Polittico_Griffoni|Polittico Griffoni]], a 15th-century Bolognese altarpiece which was dismantled in the 18th century, and whose 16 separate painted panels are now in museums across the world \n* [[Raphael]]\u2019s ''Sacrifice at Lystra'', one of the [[Raphael Cartoons]] now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum|V&A Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vam.ac.uk/blog/projects/exciting-new-plans-for-the-raphael-cartoons-and-raphael-court|title=Exciting new plans for the Raphael Cartoons and Raphael Court|last=Steel|first=Sophie|date=01 October 2019|website=V&A blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1578/the-tomb-of-raphael-in-the-pantheon Tomb of Raphael] from the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] \n* Several artworks from [[Horace Walpole]]\u2019s collections for [[Strawberry Hill House]]\n* Two sketchbooks by [[Antonio Canova]]\n\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1331/MINIATURE-BOOK-SCANNER Offiziolo di Carlo VIII] \n* The Borgherini Chapel \n\n\nOther projects have sought to \u2018digitally restore\u2019 artworks to a former state, to recreate lost artworks, or to show artworks in a changed form. Projects include: \u00a0\n\n* Digital restoration of a [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1351/canovas-equestrian-statue monumental plaster horse] by Canova, whose original is now in fragments \n\n* Digital restoration and restored facsimile of the vandalised sacred cave of [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1289/the-sacred-cave-of-kamukuwak%C3%83 Kamukuwak\u00e1] \u00a0\n* Recreation of Raphael\u2019s painting [[Christ Falling on the Way to Calvary|Lo Spasimo]] as a painting on board. The painting had been [[Transfer of panel paintings|transferred from wooden boards to canvas]] by restorers in the early 19th century, so the recreation attempts to recover an earlier stage in the history of the work. \u00a0\n* The re-creation of [[Muhammad al-Idrisi|al-Idrisi]]'s lost silver world map \n\n== Technologies ==\n\n=== Technologies for recording\u00a0 ===\nThe Factum Foundation develops many of its own recording and processing technologies, which include the Lucida 3D Scanner (designed by [[Manuel Franquelo]] with the support of Factum Foundation and Factum Arte),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=6-8 February 2019|title=A REVIEW OF RECORDING TECHNOLOGIES FOR DIGITAL FABRICATIONIN HERITAGE CONSERVATION|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/2fbe/810138da092f9ba3fcd09b430690c5e310f0.pdf|journal=The International Archives of the Photogrammetry, Remote Sensing and Spatial Information Sciences, Volume XLII-2/W9, 2019 8th Intl. Workshop 3D-ARCH \u201c3D Virtual Reconstruction and Visualization of Complex Architectures\u201d|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Del Sette, Patan\u00e9 et al.|first=|date=02 June 2017|title=Automated displacement measurements on historical canvases|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40494-017-0135-4|journal=Heritage Science|volume=5|pages=|via=Springer}}</ref> the Veronica Scanner,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/23/gallery-offers-visitors-a-3d-digital-sculpture-in-four-seconds|title=Gallery offers visitors a 3D digital sculpture in four seconds|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|date=23 July 2016|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and several book and manuscript scanners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/36/recording|title=Technology: Recording|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> The Foundation also uses established and in-development recording techniques such as [[photogrammetry]], [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag_fa/1343/panoramic-composite-photography panoramic composite photography], [[Lidar|LiDAR]] and [[White light scanner|structured light scanning]]. \n\n=== Technologies for making facsimiles\u00a0 ===\nTo make its facsimiles Factum Foundation employs a range of traditional and new technologies, often in combination. Technologies include [[Numerical control|CNC-milling]], several types of [[3D printing]], [[Molding (process)|molding]] and [[Plaster cast|plaster casting]], [[Lost-wax casting|bronze casting]], inkjet printing using an in-house printer, sculptural finishing, [[gilding]], [[scagliola]], [[Printmaking|print-making]], and the use of traditional [[Conservation and restoration of cultural heritage|restoration/conservation]] techniques.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/40/outputs|title=Technology: Outputs|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [http://www.factumfoundation.org/ Official website]\n", "text_old": "The Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation is a [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profit organization]]\u00a0founded by Adam Lowe in 2009 and located in Madrid, Spain. It develops new techniques in digital recording and processing to document artworks and cultural heritage of many different types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-factory-of-fakes|title=The Factory of Fakes: How a workshop uses digital technology to craft perfect copies of imperilled art|last=Zalewski|first=Daniel|date=21/11/2016|website=The New Yorker|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4f14250-ca3f-11e9-af46-b09e8bfe60c0|title=How digital scanning can help save art works and buildings|last=Dickson|first=Andrew|date=30/8/2019|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/madrid/2020/02/29/5e57cfacfdddfff83a8b471f.html|title=Los copiadores legales del arte antiguo|last=G\u00f3mez|first=Virginia|date=29/02/2020|website=El Mundo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoy.es/sociedad/taller-prodigios-20191109002812-ntvo.html|title=El taller de los prodigios|last=Guerrero|first=Jos\u00e9 Antonio|date=10/11/2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/apollo-awards-digital-innovation-year/|title=Digital Innovation of the Year: The Apollo Awards 2014|last=|first=|date=03/12/2014|website=Apollo Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> It is known for its facsimiles (high-resolution physical copies) of sites and objects such as the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|title=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|last=Glass|first=Nick|date=15/11/2017|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12/04/2020}}</ref> two monumental [[lamassu]] sculptures from [[Nimrud]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/mosul-statues-unveiling-scli-intl/index.html|title=Mosul takes delivery of recreated icons|last=Guy|first=Jack|date=28/10/2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/art-smashed-by-jihadists-rises-up-after-global-effort-g0dbphfd5|title=Art smashed by jihadists rises up after global effort|last=Keeley|first=Guy|date=22/10/2019|website=The Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jordantimes.com/news/region/replicas-assyrian-statues-smashed-daesh-unveiled-iraqs-mosul|title=Replicas of Assyrian statues smashed by Daesh unveiled in Iraq\u2019s Mosul|last=AFP|first=|date=24/10/2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> and the [[Sebastiano del Piombo|Borgherini Chapel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/372727/how-michelangelo-and-sebastianos-roman-chapel-was-recreated-in-london/|title=How Michelangelo and Sebastiano\u2019s Roman Chapel Was Recreated in London|last=McEwan|first=Olivia|date=17/04/2017|website=Hyperallergic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> The\u00a0 Foundation also mounts exhibitions and trains local communities across the world in the use of digital recording technologies, and is active in contemporary debates about the functions and value of facsimiles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/49/exhibitions|title=Exhibitions|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/171/trainings-collaborations|title=Trainings and Collaborations|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/the-apollo-podcast-adam-lowe/|title=The Apollo podcast: Adam Lowe|last=|first=|date=04/05/2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> It states that its aim is to \u201cbreak down the barriers between traditional and digital arts and demonstrate the importance of documenting, monitoring, studying, recreating and disseminating the world\u2019s cultural heritage.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/aboutus|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFactum Foundation works closely with [[Factum Arte]], and was established in order to take over Factum Arte\u2019s non-profit work relating to cultural heritage.\u00a0 \n\n== Cultural heritage projects ==\nNotable facsimiles made by Factum Foundation include: \n\n* The [[KV62|tomb of Tutankhamun]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-24478909|title=Which would you rather visit - a fake tomb or a real one?|last=Gee|first=Alison|date=08/11/2013|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\n* Rooms from the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]] in the [[Valley of the Kings]]. Scanning of all extant fragments from the tomb is underway, and Factum states that the finished facsimile of the tomb will be \u2018by some measures... even more complete than the original as it now stands\u2019, as it will incorporate fragments removed from the tomb in the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1502/the-tomb-of-seti-recording-and-facsimile|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> \u00a0\n* Two monumental lamassu and all extant wall and floor reliefs from the throne room of the North-West Palace of [[Ashurnasirpal II]] at Nimrud \n\n* The [[:it:Polittico_Griffoni|Polittico Griffoni]], a 15th-century Bolognese altarpiece which was dismantled in the 18th century, and whose 16 separate painted panels are now in museums across the world \n* [[Raphael]]\u2019s ''Sacrifice at Lystra'', one of the [[Raphael Cartoons]] now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum|V&A Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vam.ac.uk/blog/projects/exciting-new-plans-for-the-raphael-cartoons-and-raphael-court|title=Exciting new plans for the Raphael Cartoons and Raphael Court|last=Steel|first=Sophie|date=01/10/2019|website=V&A blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1578/the-tomb-of-raphael-in-the-pantheon Tomb of Raphael] from the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] \n* Several artworks from [[Horace Walpole]]\u2019s collections for [[Strawberry Hill House]]\n* Two sketchbooks by [[Antonio Canova]]\n\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1331/MINIATURE-BOOK-SCANNER Offiziolo di Carlo VIII] \n* The Borgherini Chapel \n\n\nOther projects have sought to \u2018digitally restore\u2019 artworks to a former state, to recreate lost artworks, or to show artworks in a changed form. Projects include: \u00a0\n\n* Digital restoration of a [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1351/canovas-equestrian-statue monumental plaster horse] by Canova, whose original is now in fragments \n\n* Digital restoration and restored facsimile of the vandalised sacred cave of [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1289/the-sacred-cave-of-kamukuwak%C3%83 Kamukuwak\u00e1] \u00a0\n* Recreation of Raphael\u2019s painting [[Christ Falling on the Way to Calvary|Lo Spasimo]] as a painting on board. The painting had been [[Transfer of panel paintings|transferred from wooden boards to canvas]] by restorers in the early 19th century, so the recreation attempts to recover an earlier stage in the history of the work. \u00a0\n* The re-creation of [[Muhammad al-Idrisi|al-Idrisi]]'s lost silver world map \n\n== Technologies ==\n\n=== Technologies for recording\u00a0 ===\nThe Factum Foundation develops many of its own recording and processing technologies, which include the Lucida 3D Scanner (designed by [[Manuel Franquelo]] with the support of Factum Foundation and Factum Arte),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=6-8 February 2019|title=A REVIEW OF RECORDING TECHNOLOGIES FOR DIGITAL FABRICATIONIN HERITAGE CONSERVATION|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/2fbe/810138da092f9ba3fcd09b430690c5e310f0.pdf|journal=The International Archives of the Photogrammetry, Remote Sensing and Spatial Information Sciences, Volume XLII-2/W9, 2019 8th Intl. Workshop 3D-ARCH \u201c3D Virtual Reconstruction and Visualization of Complex Architectures\u201d|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Del Sette, Patan\u00e9 et al.|first=|date=02/06/2017|title=Automated displacement measurements on historical canvases|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40494-017-0135-4|journal=Heritage Science|volume=5|pages=|via=Springer}}</ref> the Veronica Scanner,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/23/gallery-offers-visitors-a-3d-digital-sculpture-in-four-seconds|title=Gallery offers visitors a 3D digital sculpture in four seconds|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|date=23/07/2016|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> and several book and manuscript scanners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/36/recording|title=Technology: Recording|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> The Foundation also uses established and in-development recording techniques such as [[photogrammetry]], [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag_fa/1343/panoramic-composite-photography panoramic composite photography], [[Lidar|LiDAR]] and [[White light scanner|structured light scanning]]. \n\n=== Technologies for making facsimiles\u00a0 ===\nTo make its facsimiles Factum Foundation employs a range of traditional and new technologies, often in combination. Technologies include [[Numerical control|CNC-milling]], several types of [[3D printing]], [[Molding (process)|molding]] and [[Plaster cast|plaster casting]], [[Lost-wax casting|bronze casting]], inkjet printing using an in-house printer, sculptural finishing, [[gilding]], [[scagliola]], [[Printmaking|print-making]], and the use of traditional [[Conservation and restoration of cultural heritage|restoration/conservation]] techniques.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/40/outputs|title=Technology: Outputs|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [http://www.factumfoundation.org/ Official website]\n", "name_user": "Anachorism", "label": "safe", "comment": "edits to date formats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factum_Foundation_for_Digital_Technology_in_Conservation"}
{"title_page": "John Viener", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=June 2017}}\n{{Primary sources|date=June 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name = John Viener\n|image = John Viener by Gage Skidmore.jpg \n|image_size = \n|caption = Viener at the [[San Diego Comic-Con International]], July 2011\n|birth_name = John D. Viener\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1972|7|10}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|occupation = Actor, voice actor, writer, comedian\n| relatives = Meshulem Veiner\n|yearsactive = 1999\u2013present\n| height     = 1.91 m\n}}\n'''John D. Viener''' (born July 10, 1972) is an American actor, voice actor, writer, and comedian.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/realestate/hot-property/la-fi-hotprop-john-viener-windsor-square-home-20170711-story.html |title=\u2018Family Guy\u2019 writer-producer John Viener lists his 1920s home in Windsor Square |last=Leitereg |first=Neal J. |website=latimes.com |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |location=Los Angeles, U.S. |access-date=2019-06-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005175346/http://www.latimes.com/business/realestate/hot-property/la-fi-hotprop-john-viener-windsor-square-home-20170711-story.html |archive-date=2018-10-05 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/john-viener-mather-zickel_b_3289307 |title=John Viener & Mather Zickel Lighten Up |last=Arabia |first=C. J. |last2=Editor |first2=ContributorSenior |date=2013-05-17 |website=HuffPost |publisher=[[HuffPost]] |location=New York, United States |access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref> Viener was born in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. He is a writer and producer on the television series ''[[Family Guy]]'', where he also voices many miscellaneous characters.\n\nHe is also known as the voice of Norm the Robot on ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Actor/voice actor===\n*2002: ''[[Gilda Radner: It's Always Something]]'' - [[Chevy Chase]]\n*2002: ''[[The Late Late Show (CBS TV series)|The Late Late Show with Craig Kilborn]]'' - Himself\n*2003: ''[[The Support Group]]'' - John\n*2004: ''[[The Man in the Black Suit]]'' - The Man in the Black Suit\n*2004: ''[[The Act (short film)|The Act]]'' - Comedian\n*2005\u2013present: ''[[Family Guy]]'' - Miscellaneous characters\n*2005\u20132019: ''[[American Dad!]]'' - Miscellaneous characters\n*2005: ''[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]]'' - Weatherman Bob Fogg / Bob the Groom\n*2005: ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' - Frank\n*2006: ''[[Lighten Up]]'' - Bo's Friend\n*2006: ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'' - Agent\n*2006: ''[[Law & Order]]'' - Harvey Wallace\n*2007: ''[[The Half Hour News Hour]]'' - Bill Johnson\n*2008: ''[[The Onion Movie]]'' - Peen Out Guy\n*2008: ''[[Miracle of Phil]]'' - Medical Technician\n*2008: ''[[Wainy Days]]'' - Morgan Freeman\n*2008\u20132015: ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'' - Norm \n*2008\u20132010: ''[[Seth MacFarlane's Cavalcade of Cartoon Comedy]]'' - Miscellaneous characters\n*2009\u20132013: ''[[The Cleveland Show]]'' - Miscellaneous Characters\n*2011: ''[[Bar Guys]]'' - Guy\n*2011: ''[[Phineas and Ferb the Movie: Across the 2nd Dimension]]'' - Norm / Normbots\n*2011: ''[[Allen Gregory]]'' - CEO\n*2011: ''[[3 Weeks to Daytona]]'' - Rob\n*2012: ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]'' - Alix\n*2012: ''[[Modern Family]] - ''Matt Keneally (\"[[Tableau Vivant (Modern Family)|Tableau Vivant]]\")\n*2013: ''[[Dads (2013 TV series)|Dads]]'' - Josh\n*2014: ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]'' - I Got This Presenter\n*2014: ''[[Dumb and Dumber To]]'' - KEN Conference \n*2015: ''[[Ted 2]]'' - Police Dispatcher\n*2015: ''[[Be Cool, Scooby-Doo!]]'' - Chuck Mangum / Zaharia Warrior / Rick\n*2016: ''[[Bordertown (2016 animated TV series)|Bordertown]]'' - Steve Hernandez\n*2016: ''[[Milo Murphy's Law]]'' - Norm\n*2017: ''[[The Orville (TV series)|The Orville]]'' - Talk Show Mod